  "prompt": "How cheating is different from lying?",
  "response": "Here are key differences between cheating and lying:\n\nCheating:\n1. Involves breaking established rules or agreements\n2. Often involves deception in a specific context (relationship, exam, game)\n3. Generally involves actions, not just words\n4. Can involve direct betrayal of trust\n5. Often has more serious consequences\n6. Usually involves a deliberate violation of ethics or trust\n\nLying:\n1. Involves making false statements\n2. Can occur in any context\n3. Primarily involves verbal or written communication\n4. May or may not involve direct betrayal\n5. Consequences can vary in severity\n6. Can range from minor omissions to major fabrications\n\nWhile both involve deception, cheating typically implies a more significant breach of trust and involves active misconduct, whereas lying is primarily about communicating false information.\n\nExample:\n- Lying: Telling someone you were at work when you weren't\n- Cheating: Having an affair while in a committed relationship\n\nBoth are unethical, but cheating usually involves more direct and personal betrayal of an established agreement or relationship.",
